ists, and anthropologists examine the theory and practice of Indonesia's democratic transition and its ability to serve as a model for other Muslim countries. They compare the Indonesian example with similar scenarios in Chile, Spain, India, and Tunisia, as well as with the failed transitions of Yugoslavia, Egypt, and Iran. Essays explore the relationship between religion and politics and the ways in which Muslims became supportive of democracy even before change occurred, and they describe how innovative policies prevented dissident military groups, violent religious activists, and secessionists from disrupting Indonesia's democratic evolution. The collection concludes with a discussion of Indonesia's emerging "legal pluralism" and of which of its forms are rights-eroding and rights-protecting.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aDemocratization - Indonesia. 0aDemocratizationzIndonesia. 0aIslam and politicszIndonesia. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aAspinall, Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBowen, John R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButt, Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Sidney, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKünkler, Mirjam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKünkler, Mirjam, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLiddle, R. William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLindsey, Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMagnis-Suseno, Franz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMietzner, Marcus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 a